# üî• Lab 7: Configure Firewall Rules to Allow/Block Specific Ports in Ubuntu VM

## üéØ Objective
Use UFW (Uncomplicated Firewall) to allow/block ports like **SSH**, **HTTP (80)**, and **FTP (21)** in the VM.

---

## üõ°Ô∏è UFW Setup & Basic Rules

```bash
# Install UFW (firewall tool)
sudo apt install ufw -y

# Check UFW status with details
sudo ufw status verbose

# Allow SSH (port 22) and HTTP (port 80)
sudo ufw allow ssh
sudo ufw allow 80

# Enable the firewall
sudo ufw enable

# View numbered rules
sudo ufw status numbered

# Delete a rule by number (e.g., rule 1)
sudo ufw delete 1

# Deny and allow FTP (port 21)
sudo ufw deny 21
sudo ufw allow 21

# Check current rules
sudo ufw status numbered





# Install Nmap (port scanning tool)
sudo apt install nmap -y

# Scan FTP (port 21)
sudo nmap -sT -p 21 localhost

# Connect to FTP server
ftp localhost

# Scan HTTP (port 80)
sudo nmap -sT -p 80 localhost

# Test HTTP access (via browser or curl)
http localhost




üö´ Block HTTP (Port 80) and Test Again

# Block HTTP
sudo ufw deny 80

# Scan again to see it's blocked
sudo nmap -sT -p 80 localhost

# Check UFW rule list
sudo ufw status numbered

# Try to access HTTP again
http localhost


üîÅ Reset UFW (Clear All Rules)
sudo ufw reset


Summary
Allowed: SSH (22), HTTP (80)
Blocked/Denied: FTP (21), HTTP (80)
Tools Used: UFW (firewall), Nmap (port scanner), FTP, HTTP

